   <h1>Puyallup Road Trip [long]</h1>
   <b>&quot;bus-snob&quot; &lt;hazetguy_at_earthlink_dot_net&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2002-04-30 01:05:46+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>------=_NextPart_84815C5ABAF209EF376268C8
Content-type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII


Well last Monday I decided to put my 61 flipseat up 
for sale, and I did so on the planet. That same day I was contacted by a guy in 
Tacoma, WA who was interested in the bus. After a bunch of long e-mails, a few 
phone calls, and about 60 digital pics, we struck a deal. After considering 
a few pick-up possibilties, I threw out the suggestion of me delivering it to 
him, since there was also a VW show in Puyallup,WA, which is about 15 or so 
miles from Tacoma. Hey, I could use the road trip and show, and this would also 
save him the hassle of coming down and having to drive it back and him missing 
work. So that turned out to be the plan. On Wednesday evening I suggested to 
Rachel that she come along, since I would now be returning on Sunday, rather 
than Monday as originally planned. This way she would not miss any work and we 
could have one last trip in the bus.

After a very quick week of light maintenance to the 
bus, some flight reservations, and arranging rides home from the San Jose 
Airport on Sunday (thanks Roger!!!), the plan was set. We packed on Thursday 
night and planned on an early Friday departure for the nearly 900 mile trip. We 
were about 25 miles into the trip when we realized we forgot some things like 
toiletries, and that I forgot to unpack the camping supplies from the bus (food, 
kinves, plates, etc), but we ventured on.

Mid-Friday afternoon we entered Yreka,CA to find a 
VW shop that had 4+ splitty busses lined up along the fence that faced the 
freeway. We decided (Rachel convinced me) to stop and we did. We checked out the 
busses, bugs, type 3's and the piles of parts and had a nice chat with the 
owner. Then after a big dinner at the Black Bear Diner (?), we were back on the 
road. The hours passed and we soon decided to stop for the evening at a nice 
rest stop about 30 miles south of Eugene, OR. Oregon is strange, because it is a 
state where you can't pump your own gasoline. We stopped in a town to 
get gas (in the rain of course) where the attendant obviously didn't get out 
much. He was really proud of the mopped floors in the bathrooms and how he had 
noticed that there seemed to be alot of people stopping in who had been 
"drinkin' ". He was also overly cautious when he pulled the gas nozzle out of 
the tank, because he held his hand under the nozzle as to not get a drop of gas 
on the paint. Nice gesture, but I'd still rather pump my own gas. Oh 
well.

Saturday found us driving on I-5 for more hours, 
and it was nice to cross into Washington and go to a "normal" gas station again. 
I got some Green River soda, which I thought was in a green bottle, but it was 
actually the soda that was green. Tasted a little like liquid green jell-o. A 
few hours later we arrived at Clara's house and spent a while checking out the 
busses, seeing the parts, and watching Clara and Bruce making door and kick 
panels. After a while we decided to leave, and after we chased the dog away from 
the bag of bagels he had dragged into the yard we were off. </pre>


